, while also recommending how to confront the challenges and controversies that may arise, this original resource explains the concepts, concerns, practice, and promise of "global intellectual history," featuring essays by leading scholars on various approaches that are taking shape across the discipline.The contributors to Global Intellectual History explore the different ways in which one can think about the production, dissemination, and circulation of "global" ideas and ask whether global intellectual history can indeed produce legitimate narratives. They discuss how intellectuals and ideas fit within current conceptions of global frames and processes of globalization and proto-globalization, and they distinguish between ideas of the global and those of the transnational, identifying what each contributes to intellectual history. A crucial guide, this collection sets conceptual coordinates for readers eager to map an emerging area of study.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCivilization, ModernxPhilosophy. 0aIntellectual lifexPhilosophy. 7aHISTORY / World.2bisacsh1 aAydin, Cemil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBakhle, Janaki, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBell, Duncan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooper, Frederick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiouf, Mamadou, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHill, Christopher L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaviraj, Sudipta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoyn, Samuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoyn, Samuel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPoll